1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:06,000
Today I will show you how to turn ChatGPT into real learning tools, not just a translator.

2
00:00:06,000 --> 00:00:15,000
And today I will not speak generally, but will use specific prompts and queries that you will also be able to replicate.

3
00:00:15,000 --> 00:00:21,000
For example, today I will show all of this on the A1 level, but this video is not just for beginners.

4
00:00:21,000 --> 00:00:26,000
You will also be able to adapt all of this for yourselves, because we will be building a direct learning system.

5
00:00:26,000 --> 00:00:33,000
And you can find ready-made prompts for your level in the pinned comment under the singularity on my Telegram channel.

6
00:00:33,000 --> 00:00:35,000
And our first step is the foundation.

7
00:00:35,000 --> 00:00:39,000
You need to know precisely what level of English you currently have.

8
00:00:39,000 --> 00:00:43,000
So it's not okay to write that I have something between A2 or B1.

9
00:00:43,000 --> 00:00:49,000
You need to know your clear level, because then ChatGPT won't be able to create a program specifically for you.

10
00:00:49,000 --> 00:00:53,000
It will either be something too easy, or too difficult on the contrary.

11
00:00:54,000 --> 00:01:01,000
For this case, I have a ready-made prompt for you that you can copy and paste into your chat.

12
00:01:01,000 --> 00:01:02,000
Now I'll read it out.

13
00:01:02,000 --> 00:01:05,000
You are an experienced English language teacher.

14
00:01:05,000 --> 00:01:07,000
Help me determine my English level.

15
00:01:07,000 --> 00:01:10,000
Create a series of tasks that check.

16
00:01:10,000 --> 00:01:13,000
Vocabulary, grammar, text comprehension, speaking.

17
00:01:13,000 --> 00:01:16,000
Go step-by-step, gradually making it more difficult.

18
00:01:16,000 --> 00:01:19,000
After my answers, explain what it means for my level.

19
00:01:19,000 --> 00:01:21,000
And tell me what it is.

20
00:01:21,000 --> 00:01:27,000
And in 20-30 minutes, you will have a real understanding of where you are now and where you need to move next.

21
00:01:27,000 --> 00:01:36,000
And next, another critically important point, a mistake I constantly see, is that people open many chats and try to learn in them.

22
00:01:36,000 --> 00:01:42,000
But it is very important to open only one chat and learn specifically in it.

23
00:01:42,000 --> 00:01:46,000
Because then this chat remembers everything about you.

24
00:01:46,000 --> 00:01:54,000
What mistakes you made, what you said wrong, what you've already covered, what needs to be reinforced again.

25
00:01:54,000 --> 00:02:01,000
But when you open new chats, this memory is not saved, and you seemingly go through the same thing again.

26
00:02:01,000 --> 00:02:06,000
So we fix on one chat, one teacher.

27
00:02:06,000 --> 00:02:08,000
Well then, now our second step.

28
00:02:08,000 --> 00:02:13,000
Now we will create with you that very teacher who will teach us.

29
00:02:13,000 --> 00:02:17,000
And let's read this prompt, but you can copy it later.

30
00:02:17,000 --> 00:02:20,000
I am learning English, my level is A1.

31
00:02:20,000 --> 00:02:22,000
Here you can insert your level.

32
00:02:22,000 --> 00:02:24,000
Teach me as a patient teacher.

33
00:02:24,000 --> 00:02:30,000
From simple to complex, in short steps, with constant repetition, without overloading.

34
00:02:30,000 --> 00:02:32,000
Work with me in one chat.

35
00:02:32,000 --> 00:02:34,000
Remember her typical mistakes.

36
00:02:34,000 --> 00:02:36,000
Return to them later.

37
00:02:36,000 --> 00:02:43,000
First explain, then give practice, then repeat, speak simply and clearly.

38
00:02:43,000 --> 00:02:46,000
And with this step, you are doing a really very important thing.

39
00:02:46,000 --> 00:02:54,000
You're not just opening another random chat, you're creating your permanent, dedicated teacher.

40
00:02:54,000 --> 00:03:02,000
Well, you've already created your teacher, you've given them a goal, now let's move on to practice.

41
00:03:02,000 --> 00:03:08,000
The next step is to get certain ready-made phrases from him that match our level.

42
00:03:08,000 --> 00:03:10,000
What do we write to him?

43
00:03:10,000 --> 00:03:17,000
Give me 10 very simple English phrases for A1 level on the topic of introductions, without grammatical explanations.

44
00:03:17,000 --> 00:03:25,000
Look, here you can change both the level and the topic for which you want to receive these phrases, but overall, I think the logic is clear.

45
00:03:25,000 --> 00:03:31,000
And look what he will send us, I will add a screenshot here, he sends it directly.

46
00:03:31,000 --> 00:03:35,000
Okay, here are some very simple phrases for A1 level on the topic of introductions.

47
00:03:35,000 --> 00:03:39,000
And there's a list: hello, hi, my name is Anna, and so on.

48
00:03:39,000 --> 00:03:46,000
Basically, he did his job, he sent you not just words, but whole ready-made phrases.

49
00:03:46,000 --> 00:03:54,000
And I think you should already know that English really needs to be learned not with separate words, but with ready-made language chunks.

50
00:03:54,000 --> 00:03:58,000
The next stage for us will be listening and a prompt for listening.

51
00:03:58,000 --> 00:04:02,000
Read these phrases aloud slowly.

52
00:04:02,000 --> 00:04:04,000
And now I will show you how it works.

53
00:04:04,000 --> 00:04:10,000
Of course. I will read them clearly and slowly now, so it's easy for you to repeat.

54
00:04:10,000 --> 00:04:12,000
Ready? Let's go.

55
00:04:12,000 --> 00:04:14,000
First. Hello.

56
00:04:14,000 --> 00:04:16,000
Second. Hi.

57
00:04:16,000 --> 00:04:18,000
Third. My name is Anna.

58
00:04:18,000 --> 00:04:20,000
Fourth. I am Anna.

59
00:04:20,000 --> 00:04:22,000
Fifth. What is your name?

60
00:04:22,000 --> 00:04:24,000
Sixth. Nice to meet you.

61
00:04:24,000 --> 00:04:26,000
Seventh. I am from Ukraine.

62
00:04:26,000 --> 00:04:28,000
Eighth. Where are you from?

63
00:04:28,000 --> 00:04:30,000
Ninth. How are you?

64
00:04:30,000 --> 00:04:32,000
Tenth. I am fine.

65
00:04:32,000 --> 00:04:34,000
Repeat as many times as needed.

66
00:04:34,000 --> 00:04:36,000
If needed, tell him again.

67
00:04:36,000 --> 00:04:38,000
Like this.

68
00:04:38,000 --> 00:04:41,000
Look, here's what's important. You can listen to this once.

69
00:04:41,000 --> 00:04:44,000
I genuinely advise you not to listen to this only once.

70
00:04:44,000 --> 00:04:47,000
Why? So that you will fix it in your mind.

71
00:04:47,000 --> 00:04:50,000
Your brain will process it better.

72
00:04:50,000 --> 00:04:54,000
And will then be able to recognize it in real language, in real-life language.

73
00:04:54,000 --> 00:05:00,000
And will also be able to then suggest options for these phrases when you speak English yourself.

74
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:02,000
So listen as much as possible.

75
00:05:02,000 --> 00:05:09,000
By the way, regarding how to listen to all this, I'll add a screenshot right here now.

76
00:05:09,000 --> 00:05:13,000
So you need to click to voice what was written.

77
00:05:13,000 --> 00:05:16,000
Our next step will be reading.

78
00:05:16,000 --> 00:05:22,000
And not just any random reading, but reading exactly what you just worked with.

79
00:05:22,000 --> 00:05:33,000
That is, we will once again polish those phrases and expressions that you have just read and heard, and what our prompt for this will be.

80
00:05:33,000 --> 00:05:34,000
Look.

81
00:05:34,000 --> 00:05:37,000
Let's create a monologue story, a text for reading.

82
00:05:37,000 --> 00:05:40,000
Make it six sentences for A1 level with these phrases.

83
00:05:40,000 --> 00:05:50,000
It should sound like natural language, one paragraph, sentences logically connected, without a list and without separate phrases, so it can be said in one breath.

84
00:05:50,000 --> 00:05:54,000
And now I will show you what it created for me.

85
00:05:54,000 --> 00:05:57,000
Here I'm adding a screenshot of its answer.

86
00:05:57,000 --> 00:05:59,000
And what to do with this.

87
00:05:59,000 --> 00:06:02,000
You can read this aloud to yourself.

88
00:06:02,000 --> 00:06:04,000
You can even do it more than once.

89
00:06:04,000 --> 00:06:10,000
You can ask it to voice it again using that button I already showed you.

90
00:06:10,000 --> 00:06:17,000
And it's also important here that your brain perceives what it has heard somewhere before and starts recalling it.

91
00:06:17,000 --> 00:06:20,000
And at this moment, you are truly learning.

92
00:06:20,000 --> 00:06:24,000
And now we will move on to grammar.

93
00:06:24,000 --> 00:06:28,000
But I won't ask it now to write down the rules of use for me.

94
00:06:28,000 --> 00:06:31,000
I will try to make it just explain it to me.

95
00:06:31,000 --> 00:06:34,000
And look what we can write to it.

96
00:06:43,000 --> 00:06:45,000
Look what it answers me.

97
00:06:45,000 --> 00:06:48,000
I am, я є – this is what you say about yourself.

98
00:06:48,000 --> 00:06:54,000
When you want to say who you are, what you are like, how you feel, you start with I am.

99
00:06:54,000 --> 00:06:56,000
And life examples follow.

100
00:06:56,000 --> 00:06:58,000
In my opinion, the explanation is great.

101
00:06:58,000 --> 00:07:06,000
There are no complex terms here, it's just logically clear and simply wonderful at the beginning.

102
00:07:06,000 --> 00:07:11,000
Of course, if it's a different level, it will be a bit more complicated.

103
00:07:11,000 --> 00:07:13,000
You will see all of this in the promos.

104
00:07:13,000 --> 00:07:15,000
But for now, the logic is as follows.

105
00:07:15,000 --> 00:07:17,000
Well then, now it's time for my favorite stage.

106
00:07:17,000 --> 00:07:21,000
The stage when we start talking to our chat.

107
00:07:21,000 --> 00:07:26,000
Again, through this button, we need to switch to conversation mode with it.

108
00:07:26,000 --> 00:07:28,000
And what do we say?

109
00:07:30,000 --> 00:07:36,000
Let's now create a simple dialogue with you in English for A1 level.

110
00:07:36,000 --> 00:07:40,000
You are a new person to me, and ask me simple questions in turn.

111
00:07:42,000 --> 00:07:44,000
Of course, everything is fine.

112
00:07:44,000 --> 00:07:48,000
Let's start a simple dialogue, and I'll ask questions in turn.

113
00:07:48,000 --> 00:07:50,000
First question.

114
00:07:50,000 --> 00:07:52,000
What is your name?

115
00:08:01,000 --> 00:08:04,000
I am from Ukraine.

116
00:08:10,000 --> 00:08:14,000
I like to cook and work out.

117
00:08:23,000 --> 00:08:28,000
I think you understand that I am currently learning English.

118
00:08:30,000 --> 00:08:32,000
Of course.

119
00:08:32,000 --> 00:08:34,000
I just wanted to see that you understand.

120
00:08:34,000 --> 00:08:36,000
You're doing well.

121
00:09:01,000 --> 00:09:05,000
When you answer, use it.

122
00:09:17,000 --> 00:09:23,000
Help me write three simple sentences about myself in English for A1 level.

123
00:09:23,000 --> 00:09:27,000
Now I'll show you what it answered me.

124
00:09:27,000 --> 00:09:29,000
I'm adding.

125
00:09:29,000 --> 00:09:33,000
It has templates that I can use.

126
00:09:33,000 --> 00:09:37,000
And then it gives you a "your turn" type of prompt, meaning you should write these three sentences to it.

127
00:09:37,000 --> 00:09:45,000
In this case, when you write your sentences to it, it will correct you if something is wrong.

128
00:09:45,000 --> 00:09:49,000
Or, on the contrary, praise you if you wrote everything correctly.

129
00:09:49,000 --> 00:09:51,000
And now a very important nuance.

130
00:09:51,000 --> 00:09:55,000
After each session, you must record your progress.

131
00:09:55,000 --> 00:10:00,000
You must help this machine also with a prompt.

132
00:10:00,000 --> 00:10:08,000
Make a short summary of the lesson we covered, what mistakes are repeated, to review next time.

133
00:10:08,000 --> 00:10:10,000
No more than 100 words.

134
00:10:10,000 --> 00:10:24,000
Look, you can insert all of this both at the end of this lesson and at the beginning of the next, so you don't forget what you've already covered and can pay attention to what you need to work on more.

135
00:10:24,000 --> 00:10:32,000
And now there will be a very logical question about what to do next after you've practiced, how to do all this independently.

136
00:10:32,000 --> 00:10:38,000
And I'll tell you, you don't need to reinvent the wheel, because I've already invented it for you.

137
00:10:38,000 --> 00:10:44,000
You just need to copy this prompt and then follow our already created road map.

138
00:10:44,000 --> 00:10:46,000
Look, what a prompt.

139
00:10:46,000 --> 00:10:50,000
Conduct a daily English lesson for A1 level.

140
00:10:50,000 --> 00:10:52,000
One lesson, one day.

141
00:10:52,000 --> 00:10:54,000
Work step-by-step.

142
00:10:54,000 --> 00:10:56,000
Two-three minutes.

143
00:10:56,000 --> 00:11:00,000
In repetition, use the same words and constructions as before.

144
00:11:00,000 --> 00:11:04,000
After each step, stop and wait for my "next".

145
00:11:04,000 --> 00:11:06,000
Lesson structure: Short review.

146
00:11:06,000 --> 00:11:08,000
Short explanation of a new topic.

147
00:11:08,000 --> 00:11:10,000
Eight-ten simple phrases.

148
00:11:10,000 --> 00:11:12,000
Read them aloud.

149
00:11:12,000 --> 00:11:14,000
Short coherent text.

150
00:11:14,000 --> 00:11:16,000
Simple explanation of the meaning of constructions.

151
00:11:16,000 --> 00:11:18,000
A short dialogue.

152
00:11:18,000 --> 00:11:20,000
Three sentences of writing.

153
00:11:20,000 --> 00:11:22,000
Speak simply and don't overload.

154
00:11:22,000 --> 00:11:24,000
And that's it.

155
00:11:24,000 --> 00:11:28,000
ChatGPT will guide you further like a real teacher.

156
00:11:28,000 --> 00:11:30,000
It's just magic, I think.

157
00:11:30,000 --> 00:11:32,000
And regarding these prompts.

158
00:11:32,000 --> 00:11:36,000
They are written under a general learning system.

159
00:11:36,000 --> 00:11:44,000
If you need a specific topic or to specifically consider a grammatical structure and so on, you can, of course, adjust it.

160
00:11:44,000 --> 00:11:46,000
So adapt.

161
00:11:46,000 --> 00:11:48,000
ChatGPT is not a tutor.

162
00:11:48,000 --> 00:11:56,000
But with a well-built system, you can create a truly working simulator out of it.

163
00:11:56,000 --> 00:12:06,000
Therefore, the main thing here is to create this specific system so that it is not chaotic but broken down as we did today.

164
00:12:06,000 --> 00:12:08,000
Because that's how our brain learns thoroughly.

